<DOC><DOCNO> AP890701-0120 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-89 1902EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     07-01 0474</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0488</SECOND><HEAD>And the Rains Kept Coming</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Rain from Tropical Storm Allison fell over much of the South andSouthwest on Saturday, and remnants of the slow-moving storm floodedhundreds of Mississippi and Louisiana residents out of their homes.   More than 100 homes were flooded in Bolivar County, Miss., wherenearly 5{ inches of rain fell since midnight. Up to 3 inches wereexpected overnight in the already-saturated northern half ofMississippi.   In the southwestern Louisiana town of Oakdale, about 200 peopleremained out of their homes because of the threatening CalcasieuRiver, said Mayor George Mowad.   About 40 homes held 6 to 7 feet of water, with less in another 20to 30 homes, Mowad said. U.S. Immigration and Naturalization Serviceguards helped Louisiana National Guard troops patrol the streets,Mowad said.   Residents of a Lake Charles subdivision took pot-shots atalligators and water moccasins swimming through 6-foot-deep wateraround their houses.   The storm dumped 15 to 20 inches of rain on west centralLouisiana in the last five days.   Many streets were flooded in Arkansas City, Ark., after 3{ inchesof rain fell Saturday morning, and thunderstorms dumped 2{ inches ofrain in one hour at Alvin, Texas.   Rain and thunderstorms also extended from portions of the centralPlains into the Ohio Valley.   Heavy rain was reported in southeast Kentucky and Florida, and asevere thunderstorm in Alabama blew trees down at Chatom.   Scattered showers were reported in the Pacific Northwest and inextreme northern New England.   Partly cloudy skies prevailed in the East, where temperaturesranged from 75 to 85 degrees.   Clear skies and low humidity across much of the West allowedtemperatures to fall below freezing at some summer resorts Saturdaymorning. In the Lake Tahoe area, the mercury at Truckee, Calif.,fell to 23 degrees, making it the coldest spot in the nation, and inSouth Lake Tahoe it was 26 degrees. At Bryce Canyon, Utah, thetemperature was 29 degrees.   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 55degrees in Hoquiam, Olympia, Bremerton and Quillayute, Wash., to 107degrees in Phoenix.   The forecast for Sunday called for showers and thundershowersover eastern sections of the southern Plains, across the lower halfof the Mississippi Valley, the Ohio and Tennessee valleys, the GulfCoast states and the south Atlantic Coast states, with showers andthunderstorms most numerous over Alabama and the Ohio Valley;widespread showers over the Pacific Northwest; and widely scatteredshowers in northwest Montana and northern Maine.   High temperatures were forecast in the 80s and 90s across most ofthe nation, in the 60s and 70s in the Pacific Northwest, in the 70salong the California coast and in northern Maine, and 100 to 110degrees from southwest Texas to much of New Mexico and the desertSouthwest.</TEXT></DOC>